Binary/CLI entry point that compiles `dict.steno` into the two Neovim runtime artifacts: `out/plover-keys.json` (stroke → keyset token) and `out/snippets.json` (token → LSP snippet body). This is the production build path for the nvim plugin's lookup tables — Plover only ever sees raw keysets, so the token vocabulary and its expansion must round-trip through `expand_dict`/`build_snippets` exactly as the nvim plugin expects, or snippets silently fail to expand.

Pipeline in `run()`: reads `dict.steno` from the workspace root (`CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`), calls `parse_source` → `expand_dict` (with `None` for whatever optional param that takes, meaning no override/filter) → `build_snippets`, then hard-stops via `guard()` if `build.collisions` is non-empty — collision failure happens before any file write, so a bad build never partially overwrites `out/`. Errors from any stage (`io::Error`, parse/expand/build errors) are all flattened to `String` via `.map_err(|e| e.to_string())`, losing structured error info; `main` just prints to stderr and returns `ExitCode::FAILURE`.

`root()` locates the workspace by joining `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` with `../..` — this assumes the crate lives two directories below the workspace root (i.e., `crates/steno`); moving the crate breaks this path silently until run. `write_json` serializes an `OrderedMap` via `to_json` (both from the `steno` lib crate) and reports byte/key counts to stdout for build visibility; output ordering in the JSON is whatever `OrderedMap` preserves, which matters if downstream tooling diffs the file. `guard()` deduplicates collision messages through a `BTreeSet` before printing, so repeated collisions on the same key are only reported once, sorted alphabetically.